<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-209-688  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 209 688.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 26 1990 n579 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pie in the sky. (Uncommon Market) (the contradictory outlook fordirect-to-home satellite television in Europe) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woolnough, Roger.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Direct-to-home satellite television has been slow to catch on inEurope, and some analysts predict a financial disaster for theindustry.andP;  News Corp's Sky Television, for example, has gainedless than 500,000 homes in the UK and is losing over $3 millionweekly.andP;  Surveys by the UK's Independent Broadcasting Authorityreveal that UK citizens who are 'very interested' or 'not at allinterested' in buying or renting satellite-reception equipmenthave changed from 11 and 38 percent in 1987 to 4 and 62 percent in1989.andP;  There is also little interest in or services by satellitebroadcasting operations in France, West Germany, Italy and theScandinavian countries.andP;  British Satellite Broadcasting Ltd doesbelieve in the market's potential and will launch a competingservice to Sky in spring 1990.andP;  Continental Research alsoforecasts 5 million satellite dishes in UK homes by the end of1993.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisEuropeUnited KingdomSatellite CarriersBroadcastingDirect Satellite CommunicationsOutlookTelevision Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>